				<div id="post-660" class="hentry p4 post publish author-canuckaholic category-user-experience-design-2 category-web-design tag-ux-design tag-whitney-hess is-full comments-closed pings-open y2011 m07 d14 h04 alt slug-so-you-wanna-be-a-user-experience-designer"><h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://popdigital.ca/2011/07/14/so-you-wanna-be-a-user-experience-designer/" title="Permalink to So you wanna be a User Experience Designer?" rel="bookmark">So you wanna be a User Experience Designer?</a></h2>
<div class="entry-meta"><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-author">By </span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://popdigital.ca/author/admin/" title="View all posts by Adrian">Adrian</a></span><span class="meta-sep meta-sep-entry-date"> | </span><span class="meta-prep meta-prep-entry-date">Published: </span><span class="entry-date"><abbr class="published" title="2011-07-14T11:39:16-0700">July 14, 2011</abbr></span></div><!-- .entry-meta -->
					<div class="entry-content">
<p>I was fortunate to be able to see Whitney Hess give a talk recently at the Interlink conference in North Vancouver. Her presentation was all about UX design, and afterwards I made sure to check out her blog: Pleasure &amp; Pain.</p>
<p>Whitney has two introductory articles on becoming a user-experience designer which I found to be quite good. Here they are:</p>
<ol>
<li><a href="http://whitneyhess.com/blog/2009/06/30/so-you-wanna-be-a-user-experience-designer-step-1-resources/">Step 1: Resources</a></li>
<li><a href="http://whitneyhess.com/blog/2009/11/23/so-you-wanna-be-a-user-experience-designer-step-2-guiding-principles/">Step 2: Guiding Principles</a></li>
</ol>
